QQ9xGu_Rn6qhh-3r9kZL8Wq94kHfNMQXWjSb8pcCTxDi5XAQN96Lvo03RaoZjpBTkY-fKhp68fL9xVZfAiKMViNaOVx0hC95AVCvUk46tIvZl7bUffSyN8pdvs7__P41icDLTLXO9KiTdWFffH4AzFU5lt4phFjNWCdU0t9oigb8Tb8NnSYxKyMNMeVe4Kmsjqa-W6Byzkcz3OJs6AnosIU9F6TjfCduNaWS6p70qmoX5XnexY4tmXhy-zpehJY1QVS4qPzeUyj4gprJUZkzcj8txRtMQg6Gvg0Cs-CTAfcJ8ZMvRuLoIXO1aklDdmlOnpe9nl5S7mm2uItrFprq5rUkbZ_fEeBxD8cMbKvnXXHcFiPVykK03l8Ak-yBrqoPPzfg92he50eEHtbyd2ietz_V8f4tiVeQE5Mm6o5PjGmksxU4_DfsHtCpwVT_Q1tIeInEndlR4Ow-qD1WowjctQG7uMOFQnkVVJ8GMTuXDZzSYp5MFKq3yFxP5xsoDg_SNdclrF6H8BFIczVbaXN8uY6g6-900RawpFZGDVpGwG6I1XQ5aQWfjQsWifYIbWRqTcCF2YGlrgfMZorot1-FKL6P-e_YuFCwsvf8zJ3bYk9u3I9XqMWzF3rJuApHTVnkIWqmJTyjA7piDbh9RSRvSD3aOQTzeH8pwdWgInuyjoDI4JGmpdI4fUxRvsBh9hk9D9txHKTejO7AZhXIf72igYD5aWlfDFeBx3RDGPUo1HB0CZ5GsYWn58gO-gF57NwS-Jv3A9ib0uPbXn8dCT3-TRxxp46T00h3kn2yC-eU76x0mR9PDX5U7WBIbTcpScmw1OB6K30f4u914Fm5vQ=\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining JVM behavior**\\n\\nI need to understand why there might be differences in tracking for `getDeclaredMethod` and `Class.forName`. It could be related to how `Class.forName` is intrinsified, which might affect dynamic access tracking. It seems this method isn't being covered while others like the synthetic class$ calls are, even with certain tests involved. I wonder if the tracking only detects `Class.forName` if the argument is unknown, but it’s perplexing why there’s this distinction in coverage.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing Class.forName coverage**\\n\\nI'm considering why `Class.forName` might not be covered, possibly due to its initialization at build time before tracking. The dynamic report could relate to Native Image's `TrackDynamicAccess Preserve`. I think maybe I should call a public constructor in a fresh `ClassLoader` to resolve some issues, potentially forcing the `synthetic class$` to be initialized. It seems the coverage tracker might rely on dynamic access events and reachability metadata. I wonder if I can use `MethodHandles` for package-private classes—it’s worth exploring!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering MethodHandles use**\\n\\nI’m thinking about how `MethodHandles` are not exactly reflection but instead target internal dynamic methods directly, which isn't part of the public API. I understand we should generally avoid using them, but maybe they could become necessary after previous attempts. The user mentioned not using reflection unless required by a public API. However, invoking `synthetic class$` directly could violate the spirit of the guidelines. An alternative might be to use a custom `ClassLoader` to load `GCJInstantiatorBase`, but I’d need to construct a subclass.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test class name usage**\\n\\nI think it's better to use the target test class name, like `RuntimeResolvedType.class.getName()`. The native may still recognize it, but I need to call `Class.forName` on the test class. In a native image, it seems like `Class.forName` might need metadata. So, I’m wondering if I should add class metadata? There’s quite a bit to consider here!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_v4vNm40jrHaQlmMMNSmOZlye|fc_0f561923b218c7e30169ef788f38e881978a463581ce221a0f", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.objenesis/objenesis/1.2/src/test/java/org_objenesis/objenesis/GCJInstantiatorBaseTest.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "import java.lang.invoke.MethodHandles;\nimport java.lang.invoke.VarHandle;", "newText": "import java.lang.invoke.MethodHandle;\nimport java.lang.invoke.MethodHandles;\nimport java.lang.invoke.MethodType;\nimport java.lang.invoke.VarHandle;"}, {"oldText": "    @Test\n    void initializesGcjObjectInputStreamLookupWhenConstructed() throws Throwable {\n        TestGCJInstantiator.resetInitializationState();\n\n        Assertions.assertThatThrownBy(() -> new TestGCJInstantiator(Object.class))\n            .isInstanceOf(ObjenesisException.class)\n            .hasCauseInstanceOf(NoSuchMethodExce